diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can present with a wide range of symptoms, including psychosis (neuropsychiatric SLE), oral ulcers, atrophic scarring (discoid lupus), proteinuria (kidney involvement), and acute pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Behcet's disease can cause oral ulcers, genital ulcers, skin problems (such as acnes-like and atrophic scarring), and might be associated with psychiatric symptoms. Although less common, proteinuria and pericarditis can occur if there is vascular involvement.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD has features of multiple autoimmune diseases, including SLE, systemic sclerosis, and polymyositis. Symptoms can include muscle and joint pain, Raynaud’s phenomenon, atrophic scarring, proteinuria, and non-specific signs like acute pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: In rare cases, severe rheumatoid arthritis can present with systemic manifestations including pericarditis and proteinuria, secondary to renal involvement. Skin manifestations and oral ulcers can be seen, though atrophic scarring and psychosis are less common.

diagnoses.name: Schizophrenia
diagnoses.rationale: While it primarily presents with psychosis, it is a less likely diagnosis for the full symptom profile unless other symptoms are due to co-morbid conditions.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Sarcoidosis can involve multiple systems and present with granulomas leading to atrophic scarring, acute pericarditis, and renal involvement causing proteinuria. CNS involvement leading to psychiatric symptoms is less common but possible.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa
diagnoses.rationale: This condition involves medium-sized arteries, potentially leading to skin ulcers and scarring. Kidney involvement could lead to proteinuria, and it can also cause acute pericarditis. Psychiatric manifestations are less direct.

diagnoses.name: Wegener's Granulomatosis (Granulomatosis with polyangiitis)
diagnoses.rationale: This is a rare condition that causes vasculitis, which can lead to proteinuria due to kidney involvement, oral ulcers, and more. Cardiac involvement can include pericarditis, and lesions might heal with scarring.

diagnoses.name: Infective Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: Although primarily affecting the heart valves, systemic emboli and immune responses can cause a wide range of symptoms, including oral ulcers (Osler nodes) and kidney involvement (proteinuria). However, psychosis and atrophic scarring are less directly correlated.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.rationale: HIV can present with oral ulcers, atrophic scarring from various skin conditions, proteinuria due to kidney involvement (HIV-associated nephropathy), and pericarditis. Neuropsychiatric symptoms can occur at various stages.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with nephritis, acute pericarditis, and can also lead to seizures, atrophic scarring, and synovitis.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA)
diagnoses.rationale: Although RA is primarily known for causing synovitis, it can sometimes be complicated by pericarditis and nephritis due to systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD features symptoms of multiple autoimmune diseases, including lupus (nephritis, pericarditis) and scleroderma (atrophic scarring), and could also potentially lead to seizures.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily affecting mucosal areas, it can also have systemic manifestations including nephritis and peripheral nervous system involvement that may lead to seizures.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.rationale: Known for causing atrophic scarring due to skin and organ fibrosis; it can also affect the kidneys (nephritis) and heart (pericarditis), although seizures are less commonly associated.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: This inflammatory disease is characterized by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash, but it can also involve the heart (as pericarditis) and occasionally affects kidneys and may cause connective tissue scarring.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa (PAN)
diagnoses.rationale: A disease that causes inflammation of small and medium-sized arteries which can lead to nephritis, pericarditis, and potentially seizures due to its systemic nature.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: A rare vasculitis that can cause various symptoms including those affecting the skin (atrophic scarring), the central nervous system (seizures), and less commonly, pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disorder is known for increasing the risk of blood clots. While seizures are a common manifestation due to cerebral venous thrombosis, it can also involve the kidneys (nephritis) and less commonly, the heart.

diagnoses.name: Post-streptococcal Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.rationale: Following a streptococcal infection, this condition can cause acute nephritis. While it less commonly involves seizures, synovitis, or pericarditis, it could be a differential diagnosis based on a patient's age and medical history.

diagnoses: Evans syndrome (autoimmune hemolytic anemia and immune thrombocytopenia)
Schizophrenia (considering a primary psychotic disorder due to symptom of psychosis)

diagnoses.name: Dyshidrotic Eczema
diagnoses.description: A type of eczema characterized by small blisters on the hands and feet, usually related to stress, allergies, or moist hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder
diagnoses.description: A mental health disorder where a person has uncontrollable, reoccurring thoughts (obsessions) and behaviors (compulsions) that they feel the urge to repeat over and over.

diagnoses.name: Angioedema
diagnoses.description: An area of swelling of the lower layer of skin and tissue just under the skin or mucosa. It is often the result of an allergic reaction.

diagnoses.name: Hypersensitivity Reactions
diagnoses.description: Reactions that are exaggerated immune responses to substances that are generally not considered harmful. These can range from mild to life-threatening.

diagnoses.name: Periodontal Disease
diagnoses.description: Serious gum infections that damage the soft tissue and destroy the bone that supports your teeth.

diagnoses.name: Contact Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A skin rash caused by contact with a certain substance, which could be an overlap with symptoms seen in dyshidrotic eczema and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Atopic Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic skin condition that causes itchy, inflamed skin. It's commonly associated with a personal or family history of allergies, hay fever, and asthma.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition where hives or welts appear on the skin for more than six weeks, often without a known cause. It can be associated with other immune responses like angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder
diagnoses.description: An anxiety disorder characterized by chronic and exaggerated worry and tension. This condition could be present alongside OCD behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your immune system mistakenly attacks your body. Some autoimmune diseases can lead to symptoms like those described.

diagnoses: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD) - Crohn’s Disease & Ulcerative Colitis
Vitamin deficiencies (e.g., Vitamin B12, Folate deficiency)

diagnoses.name: Menorrhagia
diagnoses.description: Excessive menstrual bleeding.

diagnoses.name: Obstructive Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.description: A disorder causing repeated stops and starts in breathing during sleep due to throat muscles intermittently relaxing and blocking the airway.

diagnoses.name: Blepharospasm
diagnoses.description: A condition causing involuntary tight closure of the eyelids.

diagnoses.name: Kounis Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare type of allergic reaction causing acute coronary syndromes such as heart attack.

diagnoses.name: Dyspepsia
diagnoses.description: Indigestion or upset stomach, marked by discomfort or pain in the upper abdomen.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A common condition resulting from a lack of enough iron in the body, which can be associated with heavy menstrual periods.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormone, potentially leading to symptoms like fatigue, weight gain, and menorrhagia.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder causing enlarged ovaries with small cysts on the outer edges. Symptoms can include menstrual irregularity, excess hair growth, acne, and obesity.

diagnoses.name: Leiomyoma (Uterine Fibroids)
diagnoses.description: Noncancerous growths in the uterus that can cause heavy menstrual bleeding and other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where stomach contents come back up into the esophagus resulting in acid reflux and heartburn. Might be related to or mistaken for dyspepsia.
Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Anemia and difficulty concentrating are classic symptoms; periodontal disease may occur due to overall decreased body health.

diagnoses.description: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause anemia, difficulty concentrating, and migratory abdominal pain.

diagnoses.description: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.reasoning: Can lead to post-nasal drip and contribute to periodontal disease; may also cause or contribute to anemia through esophageal bleeding.

diagnoses.description: Chronic Sinusitis
diagnoses.reasoning: Responsible for post-nasal drip, and can contribute to difficulty concentrating.

diagnoses.description: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause migratory abdominal pain, anemia due to malabsorption, and might contribute to difficulty concentrating.

diagnoses.description: Inflammatory Bowel Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Conditions such as Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis can cause migratory abdominal pain and anemia, and can indirectly affect concentration through systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.description: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reasoning: Systemic disease that can cause anemia and has been associated with periodontal diseases; may also indirectly affect concentration due to systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.description: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Chronic disease that can lead to a variety of complications including periodontal disease; may cause migratory abdominal pain due to gastroparesis, and contributes to difficulty concentrating when blood glucose levels are not well managed.

diagnoses.description: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause difficulty concentrating and anemia.

diagnoses.description: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause anemia and difficulty concentrating due to the buildup of toxins in the blood; may indirectly cause migratory abdominal pain through fluid imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic illness involving your central nervous system. The immune system attacks myelin, which is the protective layer around your nerve fibers, leading to delayed response or permanent nerve damage.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraines that involve visual disturbances (aura) such as flashes of light, blind spots, or other vision changes as well as other sensations including tingling in parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include paralysis, speech difficulties, and sudden numbness or weakness, particularly on one side of the body.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief, temporary disruption of blood supply to your brain. It produces stroke-like symptoms but usually has no lasting effects.

diagnoses.name: Neuromyelitis Optica
diagnoses.description: Also known as Devic's disease, it is a chronic disorder of the brain and spinal cord dominated by inflammation of the optic nerve (optic neuritis) and the spinal cord (myelitis).

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune, neuromuscular disease that causes weakness in the skeletal muscles, which are responsible for breathing and moving parts of the body, including the arms and legs.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: Also known as Lou Gehrig's disease, it's a progressive nervous system disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, causing loss of muscle control.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Symptoms can vary greatly depending on the brain tumor's location.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves. Weakness and tingling in your extremities are usually the first symptoms. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing your whole body.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: This condition can cause a variety of neurological symptoms, including weakness, tingling, and numbness due to nerve damage. It may also lead to problems with coordination and balance, and in severe cases, cognitive difficulties.
